      <h2>Egypt's Attestation Status: Why It Matters</h2>
      <p>Egypt is not a member of the Hague Apostille Convention. This is the most important fact to understand when preparing your documents.</p>

      <p>Countries in the Hague Convention can use a simplified one-step apostille process. India, UK, USA, Canada, and Philippines use apostilles. Their documents skip the embassy attestation step entirely.</p>

      <p>Egyptian documents cannot use apostilles. Every Egyptian certificate needs the full diplomatic attestation chain. This makes the process longer and more complex than for Hague member countries.</p>

      <div class="info-box">
        <i class="fas fa-exclamation-circle"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>UAE is also not a Hague member.</strong> This means documents traveling between Egypt and UAE must follow the traditional embassy attestation route. There are no shortcuts.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>The full process involves multiple government offices in two countries. Understanding each step prevents costly mistakes and delays.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section bg-light">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>The Complete Attestation Chain for Egyptian Documents</h2>
      <p>Egyptian certificates follow a five-step chain. Each step must be completed in order. Skipping or reordering steps causes rejection.</p>

      <div class="attestation-chain">
        <div class="chain-step">
          <span class="step-num">1</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Document Issued by Egyptian Authority</strong>
            <p>Original certificate from issuing body: university, civil registry, court, or ministry. Must be an original document, not a photocopy.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="chain-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
        <div class="chain-step">
          <span class="step-num">2</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Egyptian Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA)</strong>
            <p>Attestation from Egyptian MOFA Office in Cairo or regional branches. Timeline: 3-5 business days. Cost: EGP 100-200 per document.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="chain-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
        <div class="chain-step">
          <span class="step-num">3</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>UAE Embassy Attestation in Cairo</strong>
            <p>UAE Embassy or Consulate in Egypt attests the document. Located in Zamalek, Cairo. Timeline: 5-7 business days. Cost: Variable.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="chain-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
        <div class="chain-step">
          <span class="step-num">4</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>UAE Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA)</strong>
            <p>Final attestation after document arrives in UAE. Available in Dubai and Abu Dhabi. Timeline: 1-3 business days. Cost: AED 150.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="chain-arrow"><i class="fas fa-arrow-down"></i></div>
        <div class="chain-step final">
          <span class="step-num">5</span>
          <div class="step-content">
            <strong>Arabic-English Translation (MOJ Certified)</strong>
            <p>MOJ-registered translator converts document. <a href="/resources/moj-vs-certified/">MOJ certification</a> required for government use. Certified translation sufficient for private entities.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="tip-box">
        <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i>
        <div>
          <strong>Translation Timing:</strong> Translate AFTER completing all attestation steps. If you translate before attestation, you'll need to translate again after—paying twice for the same work.
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>Learn more about the attestation process in our <a href="/services/attestation/">complete attestation guide</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

