  <section class="section bg-white">
    <div class="container content-container">
      <h2>Translation Considerations for Egyptian Documents</h2>
      <p>Egyptian documents present specific translation challenges. Experienced translators familiar with Egyptian formatting prevent rejection.</p>

      <div class="translation-issues">
        <div class="issue-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-language"></i> Egyptian Arabic vs. Standard Arabic</h3>
          <p>Egyptian official documents use Modern Standard Arabic, but formatting and terminology differ from Gulf Arabic standards. Translators unfamiliar with Egyptian conventions may misinterpret document structure.</p>
          <p>Egyptian marriage contracts and civil registry documents use specific legal phrasing. Direct word-for-word translation without understanding Egyptian legal terminology causes problems.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="issue-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-signature"></i> Name Transliteration Challenges</h3>
          <p>Egyptian names follow specific patterns: first name, father's name, grandfather's name, family name. Western transliteration varies significantly.</p>
          <p>Example: محمد عبد الرحمن can become "Mohamed Abdel Rahman," "Muhammad Abd Al-Rahman," or "Mohammed Abdelrahman." Your translation must match your passport exactly.</p>
          <div class="solution-box">
            <strong>Solution:</strong> Provide your passport copy to the translator before starting. Insist they use your exact passport spelling for all names, even if they prefer different transliteration.
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="issue-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-calendar-alt"></i> Date Format Differences</h3>
          <p>Egypt uses day/month/year format like UAE. However, older Egyptian documents may include Hijri dates alongside Gregorian dates. Some very old documents show only Hijri dates.</p>
          <p>Translators must convert Hijri dates accurately to Gregorian calendar while noting both dates in the translation. Date conversion errors cause age verification problems for birth certificates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="issue-card">
          <h3><i class="fas fa-id-card"></i> Egyptian National ID vs. Passport Numbers</h3>
          <p>Egyptian documents reference the 14-digit National ID number. UAE entities need passport numbers. Your translation should include both identifiers when present in the original document.</p>
          <p>Many Egyptian documents don't show passport numbers. The translation should note "passport number not shown on original document" to prevent questions later.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

