      <p>Understanding why Egyptian documents get rejected helps you avoid delays and repeated fees.</p>

      <div class="rejection-reasons">
        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">1</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Missing UAE Embassy Attestation</h3>
            <p>Most common error. Egyptians complete Egyptian MOFA attestation but skip UAE Embassy in Cairo. They arrive in UAE and discover the document is rejected.</p>
            <p>UAE government entities will not accept documents attested only by Egyptian MOFA. UAE Embassy attestation in Cairo is mandatory.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">2</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Wrong Attestation Sequence</h3>
            <p>Steps must happen in order: issuing authority → Egyptian MOFA → UAE Embassy → UAE MOFA. Completing steps out of order invalidates the attestation.</p>
            <p>You cannot go to UAE Embassy before Egyptian MOFA. Each step verifies the previous step's stamp.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">3</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Name Discrepancies Between Documents</h3>
            <p>Your birth certificate shows "محمد احمد علي حسن" but your passport shows "Mohamed Ahmed Ali Hassan." Even minor spelling differences between documents trigger verification delays or rejection.</p>
            <p>All document names must exactly match passport spelling after translation. Translators should harmonize name transliteration across all documents.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">4</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Expired Attestation or Document</h3>
            <p>Police clearance certificates have validity periods. UAE entities typically require police clearance issued within the last 6 months. Older certificates are rejected regardless of attestation.</p>
            <p>Some authorities also expect recent attestation stamps. If your document was attested 2 years ago but you're applying now, they may request fresh attestation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">5</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Documents from Non-Recognized Institutions</h3>
            <p>Private universities, vocational schools, or training centers not recognized by Egyptian Ministry of Higher Education cause problems. Attestation offices may refuse to attest, or UAE entities may reject despite attestation.</p>
            <p>Before starting attestation, verify your institution is officially recognized. Check the Supreme Council of Universities website for degree-granting status.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="rejection-card">
          <span class="number">6</span>
          <div class="content">
            <h3>Using Certified Instead of MOJ Translation</h3>
            <p>Egyptian expats often pay for certified translation when government entities require MOJ legal translation. GDRFA, courts, and ministries reject certified translations.</p>
            <p>Understand the difference: <a href="/resources/moj-vs-certified/">MOJ vs Certified translation guide</a>. Using the wrong type wastes money and delays applications.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

